  <a href="#1" id="1">
   TELESCOPES AND ANTENNAS
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   Ground controllers at the Goddard Space Flight Center finally made contact on Apr. 26, 1990 with the two main antennas on the $1.5 billion Hubble Space Telescope after trying for more than six hours to lock on.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   The telescope's low-gain antennas, which receive and transmit information at a much slower rate and can be used in emergencies, were working well.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   The telescope, embarking on a 15-year search for new worlds, was released from the shuttle's cargo bay on Apr. 24, 1990 after a last-minute snag that almost sent two astronauts on an emergency spacewalk.
  </a>
